{"id":"2209.12917","submitter":"Chengkang Zhou","authors":"Chengkang Zhou, Meng-Yuan Li, Zheng Yan, Peng Ye and Zi Yang Meng","title":"Detecting Subsystem Symmetry Protected Topological Order Through Strange\n  Correlators","comments":"16 pages, 14 figures","journal-ref":"PhysRevB.106.214428(2022)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevB.106.214428","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.str-el quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We employ strange correlators to detect 2D subsystem symmetry-protected\ntopological (SSPT) phases which are nontrivial topological phases protected by\nsubsystem symmetries. Specifically, we analytically construct efficient strange\ncorrelators in the 2D cluster model in the presence of a uniform magnetic field\nand then perform the projector Quantum Monte Carlo simulation within the\nquantum annealing scheme. We find that strange correlators show the long-range\ncorrelation in the SSPT phase, from which we define strange order parameters to\ncharacterize the topological phase transition between the SSPT phase at low\nfields and the trivial paramagnetic phase at high fields. Thus, the detection\nof the fully localized zero modes on the 1D physical boundary of SSPT phase has\nbeen transformed into the bulk correlation measurement about the local\noperators with the periodic boundary condition. We also find interesting\nspatial anisotropy of a strange correlator, which can be intrinsically traced\nback to the nature of spatial anisotropy of subsystem symmetries that protect\nSSPT order in the 2D cluster model. By simulating strange correlators, we,\ntherefore, provide the first unbiased large-scale quantum Monte Carlo\nsimulation on the easy and efficient detection in the SSPT phase and open the\navenue of the investigation of the subtle yet fundamental nature of the novel\ninteracting topological phases.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 26 Sep 2022 18:00:24 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"